The CompTIA Network+ certification validates your expertise and opens doors to higher-paying roles in IT and cybersecurity. Whether you are just starting your study journey or doing a final review, this guide breaks down everything you need to know to pass the N10-009 exam.

## Exam Overview

- **Certification:** CompTIA Network+
- **Exam Code:** N10-009
- **Vendor:** CompTIA
- **Cost:** $358 USD
- **Duration:** 90 minutes
- **Questions:** Up to 90 questions
- **Passing Score:** 720 out of 900
- **Format:** Multiple choice + Performance-based questions (PBQs)
- **Prerequisites:** None required (A+ recommended)

## Domain Breakdown

Understanding the exam domains and their weights is critical for efficient study planning. Focus more time on heavily-weighted domains while ensuring you cover all areas.

### Domain 1: Networking Concepts (23%)

- 1.1 Explain concepts related to the OSI model
- 1.2 Compare and contrast networking appliances, applications, and functions
- 1.3 Summarize cloud concepts and connectivity options
- 1.4 Explain common networking ports, protocols, services, and traffic types

**Key concepts:** OSI Model (7 Layers), TCP vs UDP, IPv4 Subnetting, IPv6 Addressing, DNS Resolution Process, DHCP DORA Process, NAT/PAT, Common Port Numbers

### Domain 2: Network Implementation (20%)

- 2.1 Compare and contrast various network topologies, architectures, and types
- 2.2 Compare and contrast routing technologies and bandwidth management
- 2.3 Configure and deploy common Ethernet switching features
- 2.4 Configure and deploy the appropriate wireless standards and technologies

**Key concepts:** VLAN Configuration, Spanning Tree Protocol, OSPF Routing, BGP Basics, Static vs Dynamic Routing, 802.11ax (Wi-Fi 6), PoE Standards, Link Aggregation

### Domain 3: Network Operations (19%)

- 3.1 Explain the purpose of organizational processes and procedures
- 3.2 Use network monitoring technologies
- 3.3 Explain disaster recovery and business continuity concepts
- 3.4 Use remote access methods

**Key concepts:** SNMP Monitoring, NetFlow Analysis, Syslog Levels, Network Documentation, Change Management, Disaster Recovery Planning, High Availability, SLA Management

### Domain 4: Network Security (18%)

- 4.1 Explain common security concepts
- 4.2 Compare and contrast common types of attacks
- 4.3 Apply network hardening techniques
- 4.4 Compare and contrast remote access and site-to-site security

**Key concepts:** Firewall Types (Stateful/Stateless), ACL Configuration, IDS vs IPS, VPN Types (IPSec, SSL), 802.1X Authentication, RADIUS/TACACS+, Network Segmentation, Honeypots

### Domain 5: Network Troubleshooting (20%)

- 5.1 Explain the troubleshooting methodology
- 5.2 Troubleshoot common cable connectivity issues
- 5.3 Troubleshoot common network service issues
- 5.4 Troubleshoot common performance issues

**Key concepts:** Troubleshooting Methodology, Cable Testing (TDR, Toner), Speed and Duplex Mismatch, DNS Issues, DHCP Scope Exhaustion, Routing Loops, Broadcast Storms, Latency vs Jitter


## Recommended Study Timeline

Plan for approximately **6-10 weeks** of dedicated study. Here is a suggested weekly breakdown:

- **Week 1:** Domain 1: OSI Model & Protocols — Layers, Encapsulation, TCP/IP suite
- **Week 2:** Domain 1: Network Services — DNS, DHCP, NTP, SNMP, Syslog
- **Week 3:** Domain 2: Routing & Switching — OSPF, BGP, VLANs, Spanning Tree, Trunking
- **Week 4:** Domain 2: Wireless — Wi-Fi 6/6E, Channel config, Antenna types, Site surveys
- **Week 5:** Domain 3: Network Operations — Monitoring tools, SNMP, NetFlow, Documentation
- **Week 6:** Domain 3: DR & Business Continuity — HA, Failover, Backups, SLAs
- **Week 7:** Domain 4: Network Security — Firewalls, ACLs, IDS/IPS, VPN, 802.1X
- **Week 8:** Domain 4: Hardening & Attacks — DoS, MITM, ARP poisoning, Segmentation
- **Week 9:** Domain 5: Troubleshooting Methodology — 7-step process, Cable and connectivity
- **Week 10:** Full Review: Practice tests, Subnetting drills, PBQ practice, Exam logistics

## Top Study Tips

1. **Start with the official exam objectives.** Download them from the CompTIA website and use them as your study checklist. Every exam question maps to a specific objective.

2. **Use active recall over passive reading.** Instead of re-reading notes, test yourself with practice questions after each study session. This dramatically improves retention.

3. **Focus on heavily-weighted domains first.** Domains with higher percentages appear more on the exam. Master these before moving to lower-weighted areas.

4. **Build hands-on experience.** Set up a lab environment and practice the skills you are studying. Hands-on experience is especially valuable for performance-based questions.

5. **Take practice exams under real conditions.** Time yourself, eliminate distractions, and simulate the exam environment. Review every wrong answer and understand why it was wrong.

